SIMPLE: wench
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wench
<hw>Wench</hw> <pr>(w⟦ecr⟧nch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wenche</ets>, for older <ets>wenchel</ets> a child, originally,
weak, tottering; cf. AS. <ets>wencle</ets> a maid, a daughter,
<ets>wencel</ets> a pupil, orphan, <ets>wincel</ets>, <ets>winclu</ets>,
children, offspring, <ets>wencel</ets> weak, <ets>wancol</ets> unstable,
OHG. <ets>wanchol</ets>; perhaps akin to E. <ets>wink</ets>. See
<er>Wink</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A young woman; a girl; a maiden.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lord and lady, groom and <qex>wench</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That they may send again⟦br⟧
My most sweet <qex>wench</qex>, and gifts to boot.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was received by the daughter of the house, a pretty, buxom,
blue-eyed little <qex>wench</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>W. Black.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A low, vicious young woman; a drab; a
strumpet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She shall be called his <qex>wench</qex> or his leman.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is not a digression to talk of bawds in a discourse upon
<qex>wenches</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A colored woman; a negress.</def> <mark>[Archaic, U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wench</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wench
<hw>Wench</hw> <pr>(w⟦ecr⟧nch)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Wenched</conjf> <pr>(w⟦ecr⟧ncht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Wenching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To frequent the
company of wenches, or women of ill fame.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wencher</ent>⟦br⟧
